&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;lP_Content&quot;&gt;
&lt;h2 style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Pan-Lothian Chronology&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Across all areas of Lothian, key agencies (Health, Education, Social Work and Police) have agreed to use the same chronology format known as the Pan-Lothian template.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;NHS Lothian will use the single agency format and this template should be shared with the Lead Professional when a multi-agency chronology is required. Services within NHS Lothian should start a chronology for a child, or young person, who has experienced a significant event. This may include significant events in the pre-birth period (Pan-Lothian Guidance on Chronologies. 2020).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Entries recorded within a chronology should be factual, up-to-date, and where possible should reflect the impact of the event on the child. Assumptions should be avoided. Therefore, areas of uncertainty should be verified as far as possible to ensure accuracy prior to recording.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Chronologies can identify patterns of behaviour, over a period of time that might not otherwise be apparent. Therefore, when starting a chronology retrospective significant events are important to include.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;div.SP1_AdvancedBlue { 
	background: #D2E3EA;
	border-radius: 10px 10px 10px 10px;
    box-shadow: 3px 3px 1px #888888;
